		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Not so evident Meta-play<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.22)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10885'>Wouter "Venator" Neyt</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10885&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> This article is about meta-play. As I see it, there are four ways to effectively prepare yourseleasterlingainst all the different decks in your environment. First, you should know what each shadow culture is good at and how it tries to win against your fellowship. Depending on that knowledge, you can alter your playing-style at the moment that you are playing against such a culture. For example, most players will not play all the companions in their deck against Nazgûl or Uruk. An article about this could be very interesting, if written by an experienced player and if illustrated with many examples. Own experience is essential for completely understanding this point though.<br />
<br />
<br />
Second, you can see the weaknesses of your deck against a certain culture and then look for cards that directly target that culture, or character-types, card-types (playing many conditions or not, relying on maneuver events or not) and the mechanics (the not specific ones shared by more than two cultures, like fierce, roaming, search, tracker, archery, burden-adding, twilight-adding and damage+1, for instance) often used by that culture. In my opinion, articles like this are not necessary, because everyone can easily look these things up, without much knowledge of the game itself.<br />
<br />
<br />
Third, there is a possibility to meta this direct kind of meta, but examples are not plenty, I guess for this moment there are only two: No Business of Ours against Foul Creation and Throw Yourself In Next Time against Frying Pan and Sting. You can also do that for cards that target your deck in an indirect way, for example cards that target large fellowships. I will discuss most of these too in this article under the appropriate culture.<br />
<br />
<br />
Finally, and my main subject of discussion, there are some cards that meta in a not so evident way. They target the more abstract mechanics and the specific aspects (like typical stats and strategy) of a culture. What follows is a list that tries to be exhaustive (so I will write some stuff that you already figured out yourself) for the first block, but probably isn’t. Though if this list could encourage you to be creative with meta-play, then already an important goal has been achieved.<br />
<br />
<br />
BEFORE I go off with this, I want you to realise I am not stating an opinion whether or not these cards are good. Many of these cards have never been played in a serious deck. That ‘s normal, as they are meant to only target a specific culture. If these cards do well in a regular way against other cultures, mostly they get soon accepted in the environment. <br />
ALSO this is a list, so there will be both old and new stuff. Please, do not criticise me for this. If it can’t help you, perhaps it could help some newer player. Thanks for holding this in mind when you review.<br />
<br />
<br />
Meta against Isengard Orcs:<br />
<br />
Calaglin: This Elven ally deals wounds in the regroup phase, so he actually keeps those indirect wounds from your companions.<br />
Citadel of Minas Tirith: This Gondor condition stops the Isengard Orc approach of not caring whether the skirmishes are won or lost and just dealing lots of wounds.<br />
Erland: This Gandalf ally stops two cards: Goblin Man and Palantir of Orthanc. Note that there aren’t any other shadow cards that look at hands or reveal cards from hand.<br />
Gondor’s Vengeance: Because the free peoples have the first action, this Gondor event mostly means one wound instead of three or four. For a large fellowship, it prevents one Isengard Smith from striking.<br />
Lord of Moria: Because weapon bonuses are mostly prevented, natural bonuses from other cards like Gimli, Gondor events (Dagger Strike, Still Sharp and Voice of Rauros) and especially the Dwarven condition Lord of Moria can be a solution to this.<br />
Pursuit Just Behind: Another Gondor event dealing wounds in the regroup phase, only effective when facing more than three minions, so you can have a ratio of taking one wound to prevent four or five.<br />
All cards that prevent wounds.<br />
<br />
Meta against Uruk<br />
<br />
Erland: cf. supra.<br />
Strength of Kings: This Gondor event prevents Lurtz’s Battle Cry and Savagery To Match Their Numbers.<br />
<br />
Meta against Moria<br />
<br />
Betrayal of Isengard: As Moria being the only culture that heavily relies on card drawing, this card will mostly temporally prevent one Goblin Armory. Note that every culture has one way to draw cards during the Shadow phase, but not seeing play in the current environment. (Hate and Anger, Bent on Discovery and Seeking It Always.)<br />
Caras Galadhon: This site counters the Moria Swarm approach.<br />
The Great River: This site stops the recycling mechanic on which Moria relies. (Goblin Scavengers, Host of Thousands, Relics of Moria, Foul Things, Plundered Armories) Sometimes it will counter Ulairë Nertëa (mostly used by Moria-players anyway) and Uruk Captain.<br />
Halls of My Home: This Dwarven event makes sure that the first card(s) drawn with Goblin Scimitar aren’t shadow cards<br />
Power According To His Stature: Essentially, this Shire Event kills all the exhausted minions in the skirmish, which is very hard for a Moria Swarm approach.<br />
Pursuit Just Behind: If facing no Goblin Swarms, then this Gondor event is very effective because it practically discards every exhausted minion.<br />
We Must Go Warily: In its original form, this Gondor event completely hosed the Moria swarm approach and disrupted anything else: nowadays it could only disrupt the Moria Swarm approach.<br />
<br />
Meta against Nazgûl<br />
<br />
Athelas: This Gondor possession counters Black Breath and Blade Tip. <br />
A Ranger’s Versatility: Nowadays only excellent against Nazgûl, because they have no way to counter it, and mostly it is one wound to deal two or three. In a large fellowship, it prevents Úlairë Enquëa, Lieutenant of Morgul from dealing wounds.<br />
Galdor: This Elven ally has the most effect with the high-cost Nazgûl. <br />
Stout and Sturdy: together with all other cards that could prevent a wound on the ring-bearer (too many to name them all + can be easily looked up) or heal him during a skirmish, this deals with Return to Its Master.<br />
X-cards: The Shadow cards Coming for the Ring, Dangerous Gamble, They Will Never Stop Hunting You and The Dark Lord Advances are played when the opponent has played most of his fellowship cards, so his hand has at least one Nazgûl in it. Those that trigger in the regroup phase when potential maneuver and skirmish events are already played, have the most chance of having the wanted effect.<br />
<br />
Meta against Sauron<br />
<br />
Athelas: This Gondor possession counters Desperate Defense of the Ring, Thin and Stretched and You Bring Great Evil<br />
Calaglin: This Elven ally deals wounds in the regroup phase, so he actually keeps those direct wounds from your companions. This counters Morgul Slayer and Orc Slayer.<br />
Elrond, Herald to Gil-galad: This Elven ally heals in the regroup phase and could prevent an exhausted companion from a directed wound of Morgul Slayer and Orc Slayer. <br />
Gondor’s Vengeance: This Gondor event deals with Morgul Slayer and Orc Slayer and potentially reduces the card drawing with Spies of Mordor.<br />
Master of Healing: cf. Elrond, but now as an event.<br />
Old Noakes: This Hobbit ally stops Tower of Barad-Dûr, Band of the Eye, Orc Inquisitor, Tower Lieutenant.<br />
Strength of Kings: This Gondor event prevents Enduring Evil. <br />
All cards that prevent wounds: This prevents the directed wounds from Hate, Morgul Slayer and Orc Slayer.<br />
<br />
<br />
Remark: in this game, the Shadow side has little options to meta in a not evident way against the Free peoples. This is a good thing because it would make certain cultures associate with each other, and so it would reduce the number of deck-types and raise the predictibality of the game.<br />
Conclusion: The more this card is good in a regular way, the more it will see play in the environment. Unlike evident meta which has to be discarded if not playing against the targeted culture, every card (with only a few exceptions) listed here can be played anytime. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=4079&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
